# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albemarle-county-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County was created in 1744 from the western portion of Goochland County, though portions of Albemarle were later carved out to create other counties.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County was named in honor of Willem Anne van Keppel, 2nd Earl of Albemarle.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Its most famous inhabitant was Thomas Jefferson, who built his estate home, Monticello, in the county.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] At the time of European encounter, the inhabitants of the area that became Albemarle County were a Siouan-speaking tribe called the Saponi.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] In 1744, the Virginia General Assembly created Albemarle County from the western portion of Goochland County.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The county was named in honor of Willem Anne van Keppel, 2nd Earl of Albemarle and titular Governor of Virginia at the time.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The large county was partitioned in 1761, forming Buckingham and Amherst counties, at which time the county seat was moved from the formerly central Scottsville to a piece of newly central land, christened Charlottesville.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] In 1777, Albemarle County was divided and Fluvanna County established, finalizing the boundaries of modern Albemarle County.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County is well known for its association with President and Founding Father Thomas Jefferson, who was born in the county at Shadwell, though it was then part of Goochland County.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] However, his home of Monticello is located in the county.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] When the American Revolutionary War started in 1775, Jefferson was made colonel of the Albemarle Militia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] During the Civil War, the Battle of Rio Hill was a skirmish in which Union cavalry raided a Confederate camp in Albemarle County, Virginia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Until the Civil War, the majority of Albemarle County's population consisted of enslaved African Americans.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 726 square miles (1,880 km2), of which 721 square miles (1,870 km2) is land and 5 square miles (13 km2) (0.7%) is water.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The Rivanna River's south fork forms in Albemarle County and was historically important for transportation.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The south fork flows in-between Darden Towe Park and Pen Park.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Boat ramp access is available at Darden Towe Park.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The James River acts as a natural border between Albemarle and Buckingham Counties.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle's western border with Augusta and Rockingham Counties is located within the Shenandoah National Park.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County borders eight other counties, more than any other county in Virginia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 112,395.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 20.3% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.4% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] For every 100 females there were 91.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.1 males age 18 and over.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The racial makeup of the county was 72.8% White, 8.9% Black or African American, 0.3% American Indian and Alaska Native, 7.3% Asian, 0.0% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 3.6% from some other race, and 7.0% from two or more races.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 7.5% of the population.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 59.6% of residents lived in urban areas, while 40.4% lived in rural areas.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 43,468 households in the county, of which 28.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 28.1% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] About 28.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 47,291 housing units, of which 8.1% were vacant.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Among occupied housing units, 64.7% were owner-occupied and 35.3% were renter-occupied.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.6% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.0%.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The largest self-reported ancestry groups in Albemarle County are English 16.3%, German 16.0%, Irish 12.7%, "American" 11.4% and Italian 5.2%.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] As of the census of 2010, there were 98,970 people, 38,157 households, and 24,578 families residing in the county.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The population density was 137 people per square mile (53 people/km2).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 42,122 housing units at an average density of 58 units per square mile (22 units/km2).
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The racial makeup of the county was 80.6% White, 9.7% Black or African American, 0.3% Native American, 4.7% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 2.3% from other races, and 2.4% from two or more races.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 5.5% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] There were 38,157 households, out of which 28.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.4% were married couples living together, 9.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.6% were non-families.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 28.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 25.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The average household size was 2.41 and the average family size was 2.96.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] In the county, the population was spread out, with 21.5% under the age of 18, 12.3% from 18 to 24, 24.7% from 25 to 44, 27.2% from 45 to 64, and 14.3% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] For every 100 females there were 92.69 males.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] For every 100 females aged 18 and over, there were 89.59 males.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 22% of Albemarle residents have a graduate or professional degree, compared with 10% nationwide.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The median income for a household in the county was $63,001, and the median income for a family was $98,934.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Males had a median income of $55,530 versus $52,211 for females.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The per capita income for the county was $36,718.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] About 3.8% of families and 10.4% of the population were below the poverty line, including 8.0% of those under age 18 and 2.4% of those age 65 or over.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 35% of people working in Albemarle live in the county, while 65% commute in.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 19% of those commuting in live in Charlottesville, while the remainder live in the surrounding counties.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 26,800 people commute out of Albemarle for work.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] 48% of which commute to Charlottesville, making up 51% of Charlottesville's in-commuters.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] In 2022, Albemarle had a 2.7% unemployment rate, compared with a national rate of 3.6%.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle is governed by an elected six-member Board of Supervisors.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Management of the county is vested in a Board-appointed County Executive.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The nonpartisan School Board is also elected.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County has two branches of law enforcement, the Albemarle County Police Department, which handles criminal matters and is directed by the appointed police chief, Colonel Sean Reeves.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The second branch is the Albemarle County Sheriff's Office, which handles civil service in the county, and they are directed by the elected Sheriff Chan Bryant.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle County Fire Rescue (ACFR) provides essential emergency services to the residents and visitors of Albemarle County including, fire suppression, emergency medical treatment, and transport, technical rescue, water rescue, and hazardous materials mitigation.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] In addition, the department provides a wide array of non-emergency services such as investigations, business inspections, burn permits, child safety seat inspections, smoke detector installations, public education, and emergency management.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Services are provided through a combination of career staff, nine volunteer fire and rescue agencies, and regional partners.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The Albemarle County Sheriff's Office (ACSO) and the Albemarle County Police Department (ACPD) provide law enforcement services in the county.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The ACSO was created in 1745 when Joseph Thompson was appointed as the first sheriff.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Then in 1895, citizens started electing sheriffs for 4-year terms.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Lucian Watts was the first elected sheriff.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] As of 2022 the sheriff is Chan Bryant, the county's first woman sheriff.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Prior to 1983, local county governments could create a police force by a simple vote held by their respective board of supervisors.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] In February 1983 the Virginia General Assembly restricted the authority of county governments to create police forces without a voter referendum.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The law did not go into effect until July 1983: On May 11, 1983, before the law took effect, the Albemarle County Board of Supervisors passed an ordinance creating the Albemarle County Police Department.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] That original ordinance provided for a police chief and five full time officers.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] As of 2022 the chief of police is Sean Reeves.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The ACPD currently has 140 sworn officers, 23 civilian employees, and 3 animal control officers.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Albemarle is represented by Democrat Creigh Deeds in the Virginia State Senate; Democrats Katrina Callsen and Amy Laufer represent the county in the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Republican John McGuire represents most of the county in the U.S.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Democrat Eugene Vindman represents a small sliver in the most northwestern portion of Albemarle County.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] For much of the second half of the 20th century, Albemarle County was heavily Republican, like most of this part of Virginia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] However, the Republican edge narrowed significantly in the 1990s, in part due to the influence of the University of Virginia.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] In 2004, John Kerry carried it by two points, becoming the first Democrat to win the county since 1948.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] It swung hard to Barack Obama in 2008, and since then, it has become one of the few Democratic bastions in central Virginia, though it is not as overwhelmingly Democratic as Charlottesville.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The Albemarle County Public School System operates public education in the county.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] It provides education to nearly 14,000 students including preschool through high school.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The School Board and the Superintendent, Matthew Haas, work closely together in operating the Albemarle County Public School System.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Many private schools in Albemarle serve the county and students from surrounding areas.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Some students attend several private schools in the City of Charlottesville.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Jefferson-Madison Regional Library is the regional library system that provides services to the citizens of Albemarle.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Portions of the University of Virginia are located within Albemarle County.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] The city of Charlottesville is enclaved within Albemarle County.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Under Virginia law in effect since 1871, all municipalities in the state incorporated as cities are legally and politically independent of any county.
[src:albemarle-county-virginia/albemarle-county-virginia] Many of these unincorporated areas have Charlottesville addresses.
